{"cues": [{"duration": 16.88, "start": 0.0, "text": "[Submit subtitle corrections at criblate.com]"}, {"duration": 2.46, "start": 16.88, "text": "I'd like to revisit a deceptively simple question"}, {"duration": 2.66, "start": 19.34, "text": "that I asked in the very first video of this series."}, {"duration": 0.86, "start": 22.7, "text": "What are vectors?"}, {"duration": 3.037, "start": 24.48, "text": "Is a two-dimensional vector, for example, fundamentally an arrow on"}, {"duration": 3.083, "start": 27.517, "text": "a flat plane that we can describe with coordinates for convenience?"}, {"duration": 3.399, "start": 30.86, "text": "Or is it fundamentally that pair of real numbers which"}, {"duration": 3.461, "start": 34.259, "text": "is just nicely visualized as an arrow on a flat plane?"}, {"duration": 2.88, "start": 38.48, "text": "Or are both of these just manifestations of something deeper?"}, {"duration": 3.12, "start": 42.3, "text": "On the one hand, defining vectors as primarily being"}, {"duration": 3.06, "start": 45.42, "text": "a list of numbers feels clear-cut and unambiguous."}, {"duration": 4.327, "start": 49.06, "text": "It makes things like four-dimensional vectors or 100-dimensional vectors sound like real,"}, {"duration": 2.333, "start": 53.387, "text": "concrete ideas that you can actually work with."}, {"duration": 3.999, "start": 55.72, "text": "When otherwise, an idea like four dimensions is just a vague geometric"}, {"duration": 3.941, "start": 59.719, "text": "notion that's difficult to describe without waving your hands a bit."}, {"duration": 3.658, "start": 65.54, "text": "But on the other hand, a common sensation for those who actually work with"}, {"duration": 3.756, "start": 69.198, "text": "linear algebra, especially as you get more fluent with changing your basis,"}, {"duration": 3.51, "start": 72.954, "text": "is that you're dealing with a space that exists independently from the"}, {"duration": 4.151, "start": 76.464, "text": "coordinates that you give it, and that coordinates are actually somewhat arbitrary,"}, {"duration": 3.065, "start": 80.615, "text": "depending on what you happen to choose as your basis vectors."}, {"duration": 3.36, "start": 84.48, "text": "Core topics in linear algebra, like determinants and eigenvectors,"}, {"duration": 2.8, "start": 87.84, "text": "seem indifferent to your choice of coordinate systems."}, {"duration": 3.461, "start": 91.44, "text": "The determinant tells you how much a transformation scales areas,"}, {"duration": 4.419, "start": 94.901, "text": "and eigenvectors are the ones that stay on their own span during a transformation."}, {"duration": 2.798, "start": 100.0, "text": "But both of these properties are inherently spatial,"}, {"duration": 4.358, "start": 102.798, "text": "and you can freely change your coordinate system without changing the underlying"}, {"duration": 1.184, "start": 107.156, "text": "values of either one."}, {"duration": 3.161, "start": 110.76, "text": "But if vectors are not fundamentally lists of real numbers,"}, {"duration": 3.161, "start": 113.921, "text": "and if their underlying essence is something more spatial,"}, {"duration": 3.858, "start": 117.082, "text": "that just begs the question of what mathematicians mean when they use a"}, {"duration": 1.5, "start": 120.94, "text": "word like space or spatial."}, {"duration": 3.123, "start": 123.4, "text": "To build up to where this is going, I'd actually like to spend the"}, {"duration": 3.265, "start": 126.523, "text": "bulk of this video talking about something which is neither an arrow"}, {"duration": 3.312, "start": 129.788, "text": "nor a list of numbers, but also has vector-ish qualities \u2013 functions."}, {"duration": 4.14, "start": 133.74, "text": "You see, there's a sense in which functions are actually just another type of vector."}, {"duration": 2.781, "start": 139.76, "text": "In the same way that you can add two vectors together,"}, {"duration": 3.399, "start": 142.541, "text": "there's also a sensible notion for adding two functions, f and g,"}, {"duration": 1.7, "start": 145.94, "text": "to get a new function, f plus g."}, {"duration": 3.265, "start": 148.2, "text": "It's one of those things where you kind of already know what it's going to be,"}, {"duration": 1.675, "start": 151.465, "text": "but actually phrasing it is a mouthful."}, {"duration": 4.385, "start": 153.96, "text": "The output of this new function at any given input, like negative four,"}, {"duration": 5.249, "start": 158.345, "text": "is the sum of the outputs of f and g when you evaluate them each at that same input,"}, {"duration": 0.926, "start": 163.594, "text": "negative four."}, {"duration": 4.16, "start": 165.42, "text": "Or more generally, the value of the sum function at any"}, {"duration": 4.16, "start": 169.58, "text": "given input x is the sum of the values f(x) plus g(x)."}, {"duration": 3.526, "start": 180.7, "text": "This is pretty similar to adding vectors coordinate by coordinate,"}, {"duration": 4.274, "start": 184.226, "text": "it's just that there are, in a sense, infinitely many coordinates to deal with."}, {"duration": 4.432, "start": 191.1, "text": "Similarly, there's a sensible notion for scaling a function by a real number,"}, {"duration": 2.648, "start": 195.532, "text": "just scale all of the outputs by that number."}, {"duration": 3.404, "start": 200.24, "text": "And again, this is analogous to scaling a vector coordinate by coordinate,"}, {"duration": 2.576, "start": 203.644, "text": "it just feels like there's infinitely many coordinates."}, {"duration": 4.592, "start": 208.9, "text": "Now, given that the only thing vectors can really do is get added together or scaled,"}, {"duration": 4.268, "start": 213.492, "text": "it feels like we should be able to take the same useful constructs and problem"}, {"duration": 4.052, "start": 217.76, "text": "solving techniques of linear algebra that were originally thought about in"}, {"duration": 3.728, "start": 221.812, "text": "the context of arrows and space and apply them to functions as well."}, {"duration": 4.472, "start": 226.54, "text": "For example, there's a perfectly reasonable notion of a linear transformation"}, {"duration": 4.588, "start": 231.012, "text": "for functions, something that takes in one function and turns it into another."}, {"duration": 2.96, "start": 239.82, "text": "One familiar example comes from calculus, the derivative."}, {"duration": 3.72, "start": 243.42, "text": "It's something which transforms one function into another function."}, {"duration": 3.956, "start": 248.72, "text": "Sometimes in this context you'll hear these called operators instead of transformations,"}, {"duration": 1.304, "start": 252.676, "text": "but the meaning is the same."}, {"duration": 2.574, "start": 256.24, "text": "A natural question you might want to ask is what it"}, {"duration": 2.726, "start": 258.814, "text": "means for a transformation of functions to be linear."}, {"duration": 4.075, "start": 262.44, "text": "The formal definition of linearity is relatively abstract and symbolically driven"}, {"duration": 3.925, "start": 266.515, "text": "compared to the way that I first talked about it in chapter 3 of this series."}, {"duration": 3.256, "start": 270.44, "text": "But the reward of abstractness is that we'll get something"}, {"duration": 3.144, "start": 273.696, "text": "general enough to apply to functions as well as arrows."}, {"duration": 3.444, "start": 279.18, "text": "A transformation is linear if it satisfies two properties,"}, {"duration": 2.376, "start": 282.624, "text": "commonly called additivity and scaling."}, {"duration": 4.432, "start": 286.04, "text": "Additivity means that if you add two vectors, v and w,"}, {"duration": 7.059, "start": 290.472, "text": "then apply a transformation to their sum, you get the same result as if you added the"}, {"duration": 2.709, "start": 297.531, "text": "transformed versions of v and w."}, {"duration": 5.015, "start": 304.52, "text": "The scaling property is that when you scale a vector v by some number,"}, {"duration": 4.8, "start": 309.535, "text": "then apply the transformation, you get the same ultimate vector as"}, {"duration": 4.585, "start": 314.335, "text": "if you scaled the transformed version of v by that same amount."}, {"duration": 3.726, "start": 321.7, "text": "The way you'll often hear this described is that linear transformations"}, {"duration": 3.674, "start": 325.426, "text": "preserve the operations of vector addition and scalar multiplication."}, {"duration": 3.914, "start": 332.2, "text": "The idea of gridlines remaining parallel and evenly spaced that I've"}, {"duration": 3.857, "start": 336.114, "text": "talked about in past videos is really just an illustration of what"}, {"duration": 4.029, "start": 339.971, "text": "these two properties mean in the specific case of points in 2D space."}, {"duration": 3.232, "start": 344.88, "text": "One of the most important consequences of these properties,"}, {"duration": 2.794, "start": 348.112, "text": "which makes matrix-vector multiplication possible,"}, {"duration": 3.725, "start": 350.906, "text": "is that a linear transformation is completely described by where it"}, {"duration": 1.369, "start": 354.631, "text": "takes the basis vectors."}, {"duration": 4.819, "start": 357.72, "text": "Since any vector can be expressed by scaling and adding the basis vectors in some way,"}, {"duration": 4.315, "start": 362.539, "text": "finding the transformed version of a vector comes down to scaling and adding"}, {"duration": 3.586, "start": 366.854, "text": "the transformed versions of the basis vectors in that same way."}, {"duration": 4.5, "start": 372.28, "text": "As you'll see in just a moment, this is as true for functions as it is for arrows."}, {"duration": 4.026, "start": 378.36, "text": "For example, calculus students are always using the fact that the derivative is"}, {"duration": 4.434, "start": 382.386, "text": "additive and has the scaling property, even if they haven't heard it phrased that way."}, {"duration": 2.989, "start": 388.14, "text": "If you add two functions, then take the derivative,"}, {"duration": 4.044, "start": 391.129, "text": "it's the same as first taking the derivative of each one separately,"}, {"duration": 1.407, "start": 395.173, "text": "then adding the result."}, {"duration": 3.115, "start": 400.14, "text": "Similarly, if you scale a function, then take the derivative,"}, {"duration": 3.625, "start": 403.255, "text": "it's the same as first taking the derivative, then scaling the result."}, {"duration": 3.028, "start": 410.28, "text": "To really drill in the parallel, let's see what it might"}, {"duration": 2.812, "start": 413.308, "text": "look like to describe the derivative with a matrix."}, {"duration": 3.307, "start": 416.98, "text": "This will be a little tricky, since function spaces have a tendency to be"}, {"duration": 3.533, "start": 420.287, "text": "infinite dimensional, but I think this exercise is actually quite satisfying."}, {"duration": 4.618, "start": 424.84, "text": "Let's limit ourselves to polynomials, things like x squared plus 3x plus 5,"}, {"duration": 2.402, "start": 429.458, "text": "or 4x to the seventh minus 5x squared."}, {"duration": 4.054, "start": 432.33, "text": "Each of the polynomials in our space will only have finitely many terms,"}, {"duration": 4.616, "start": 436.384, "text": "but the full space is going to include polynomials with arbitrarily large degree."}, {"duration": 3.325, "start": 442.22, "text": "The first thing we need to do is give coordinates to this space,"}, {"duration": 1.715, "start": 445.545, "text": "which requires choosing a basis."}, {"duration": 5.155, "start": 448.18, "text": "Since polynomials are already written down as the sum of scaled powers of the variable x,"}, {"duration": 4.345, "start": 453.335, "text": "it's pretty natural to just choose pure powers of x as the basis function."}, {"duration": 5.42, "start": 458.28, "text": "In other words, our first basis function will be the constant function, b0(x) equals 1."}, {"duration": 3.861, "start": 464.18, "text": "The second basis function will be b1(x) equals x,"}, {"duration": 5.279, "start": 468.041, "text": "then b2(x) equals x squared, then b3(x) equals x cubed, and so on."}, {"duration": 4.315, "start": 473.86, "text": "The role that these basis functions serve will be similar to the roles of i-hat,"}, {"duration": 2.805, "start": 478.175, "text": "j-hat, and k-hat in the world of vectors as arrows."}, {"duration": 3.094, "start": 482.12, "text": "Since our polynomials can have arbitrarily large degree,"}, {"duration": 2.266, "start": 485.214, "text": "this set of basis functions is infinite."}, {"duration": 3.537, "start": 488.24, "text": "But that's okay, it just means that when we treat our polynomials as vectors,"}, {"duration": 2.343, "start": 491.777, "text": "they're going to have infinitely many coordinates."}, {"duration": 4.168, "start": 495.6, "text": "A polynomial like x squared plus 3x plus 5, for example,"}, {"duration": 5.732, "start": 499.768, "text": "would be described with the coordinates 5, 3, 1, then infinitely many zeros."}, {"duration": 3.964, "start": 506.1, "text": "You'd read this as saying that it's 5 times the first basis function,"}, {"duration": 4.597, "start": 510.064, "text": "plus 3 times that second basis function, plus 1 times the third basis function,"}, {"duration": 4.539, "start": 514.661, "text": "and then none of the other basis functions should be added from that point on."}, {"duration": 6.475, "start": 520.62, "text": "The polynomial 4x to the seventh minus 5x squared would have the coordinates 0,"}, {"duration": 5.245, "start": 527.095, "text": "0, negative 5, 0, 0, 0, 0, 4, then an infinite string of zeros."}, {"duration": 4.537, "start": 533.26, "text": "In general, since every individual polynomial has only finitely many terms,"}, {"duration": 5.203, "start": 537.797, "text": "its coordinates will be some finite string of numbers with an infinite tail of zeros."}, {"duration": 3.469, "start": 546.9, "text": "In this coordinate system, the derivative is described with"}, {"duration": 2.822, "start": 550.369, "text": "an infinite matrix that's mostly full of zeros,"}, {"duration": 4.409, "start": 553.191, "text": "but which has the positive integers counting down on this offset diagonal."}, {"duration": 2.868, "start": 558.4, "text": "I'll talk about how you could find this matrix in just a moment,"}, {"duration": 3.092, "start": 561.268, "text": "but the best way to get a feel for it is to just watch it in action."}, {"duration": 6.135, "start": 564.97, "text": "Take the coordinates representing the polynomial x cubed plus 5x squared plus 4x plus 5,"}, {"duration": 3.835, "start": 571.105, "text": "then put those coordinates on the right of the matrix."}, {"duration": 4.77, "start": 580.41, "text": "The only term that contributes to the first coordinate of the result is 1 times 4,"}, {"duration": 3.2, "start": 585.18, "text": "which means the constant term in the result will be 4."}, {"duration": 4.28, "start": 590.1, "text": "This corresponds to the fact that the derivative of 4x is the constant 4."}, {"duration": 5.019, "start": 595.64, "text": "The only term contributing to the second coordinate of the matrix-vector product"}, {"duration": 5.081, "start": 600.659, "text": "is 2 times 5, which means the coefficient in front of x in the derivative is 10."}, {"duration": 2.78, "start": 606.5, "text": "That one corresponds to the derivative of 5x squared."}, {"duration": 2.996, "start": 610.78, "text": "Similarly, the third coordinate in the matrix-vector"}, {"duration": 2.304, "start": 613.776, "text": "product comes down to taking 3 times 1."}, {"duration": 4.08, "start": 617.66, "text": "This one corresponds to the derivative of x cubed being 3x squared."}, {"duration": 1.94, "start": 623.08, "text": "And after that, it'll be nothing but zeros."}, {"duration": 2.92, "start": 626.88, "text": "What makes this possible is that the derivative is linear."}, {"duration": 2.608, "start": 631.64, "text": "And for those of you who like to pause and ponder,"}, {"duration": 3.391, "start": 634.248, "text": "you could construct this matrix by taking the derivative of each"}, {"duration": 3.861, "start": 637.639, "text": "basis function and putting the coordinates of the results in each column."}, {"duration": 4.081, "start": 659.78, "text": "So, surprisingly, matrix-vector multiplication and taking a derivative,"}, {"duration": 3.162, "start": 663.861, "text": "which at first seem like completely different animals,"}, {"duration": 2.817, "start": 667.023, "text": "are both just really members of the same family."}, {"duration": 3.576, "start": 671.22, "text": "In fact, most of the concepts I've talked about in this series with"}, {"duration": 4.484, "start": 674.796, "text": "respect to vectors as arrows in space, things like the dot product or eigenvectors,"}, {"duration": 2.509, "start": 679.28, "text": "have direct analogs in the world of functions,"}, {"duration": 4.751, "start": 681.789, "text": "though sometimes they go by different names, things like inner product or eigenfunction."}, {"duration": 2.48, "start": 688.4, "text": "So back to the question of what is a vector."}, {"duration": 4.28, "start": 691.56, "text": "The point I want to make here is that there are lots of vector-ish things in math."}, {"duration": 4.641, "start": 695.84, "text": "As long as you're dealing with a set of objects where there's a reasonable notion of"}, {"duration": 4.365, "start": 700.481, "text": "scaling and adding, whether that's a set of arrows in space, lists of numbers,"}, {"duration": 3.481, "start": 704.846, "text": "functions, or whatever other crazy thing you choose to define,"}, {"duration": 3.536, "start": 708.327, "text": "all of the tools developed in linear algebra regarding vectors,"}, {"duration": 3.757, "start": 711.863, "text": "linear transformations and all that stuff, should be able to apply."}, {"duration": 2.311, "start": 717.48, "text": "Take a moment to imagine yourself right now as a"}, {"duration": 2.649, "start": 719.791, "text": "mathematician developing the theory of linear algebra."}, {"duration": 4.43, "start": 722.44, "text": "You want all of the definitions and discoveries of your work to apply to all"}, {"duration": 4.43, "start": 726.87, "text": "of the vector-ish things in full generality, not just to one specific case."}, {"duration": 4.74, "start": 733.4, "text": "These sets of vector-ish things, like arrows or lists of numbers or functions,"}, {"duration": 1.58, "start": 738.14, "text": "are called vector spaces."}, {"duration": 2.678, "start": 740.58, "text": "And what you as the mathematician might want to do is say,"}, {"duration": 2.678, "start": 743.258, "text": "hey everyone, I don't want to have to think about all the"}, {"duration": 3.324, "start": 745.936, "text": "different types of crazy vector spaces that you all might come up with."}, {"duration": 3.064, "start": 749.26, "text": "So what you do is establish a list of rules that"}, {"duration": 2.936, "start": 752.324, "text": "vector addition and scaling have to abide by."}, {"duration": 3.749, "start": 756.4, "text": "These rules are called axioms, and in the modern theory of linear algebra,"}, {"duration": 3.446, "start": 760.149, "text": "there are eight axioms that any vector space must satisfy if all of"}, {"duration": 3.445, "start": 763.595, "text": "the theory and constructs that we've discovered are going to apply."}, {"duration": 3.435, "start": 767.7, "text": "I'll leave them on the screen here for anyone who wants to pause and ponder,"}, {"duration": 3.435, "start": 771.135, "text": "but basically it's just a checklist to make sure that the notions of vector"}, {"duration": 3.57, "start": 774.57, "text": "addition and scalar multiplication do the things that you'd expect them to do."}, {"duration": 3.795, "start": 778.72, "text": "These axioms are not so much fundamental rules of nature as they are an"}, {"duration": 3.368, "start": 782.515, "text": "interface between you, the mathematician, discovering results,"}, {"duration": 4.597, "start": 785.883, "text": "and other people who might want to apply those results to new sorts of vector spaces."}, {"duration": 3.506, "start": 791.42, "text": "If, for example, someone defines some crazy type of vector space,"}, {"duration": 4.099, "start": 794.926, "text": "like the set of all pi creatures with some definition of adding and scaling"}, {"duration": 4.099, "start": 799.025, "text": "pi creatures, these axioms are like a checklist of things that they need to"}, {"duration": 4.153, "start": 803.124, "text": "verify about their definitions before they can start applying the results of"}, {"duration": 0.863, "start": 807.277, "text": "linear algebra."}, {"duration": 2.712, "start": 808.82, "text": "And you, as the mathematician, never have to think about"}, {"duration": 2.808, "start": 811.532, "text": "all the possible crazy vector spaces people might define."}, {"duration": 3.442, "start": 814.86, "text": "You just have to prove your results in terms of these axioms so"}, {"duration": 4.261, "start": 818.302, "text": "anyone whose definitions satisfy those axioms can happily apply your results,"}, {"duration": 2.677, "start": 822.563, "text": "even if you never thought about their situation."}, {"duration": 4.271, "start": 826.52, "text": "As a consequence, you'd tend to phrase all of your results pretty abstractly,"}, {"duration": 2.663, "start": 830.791, "text": "which is to say, only in terms of these axioms,"}, {"duration": 4.826, "start": 833.454, "text": "rather than centering on a specific type of vector, like arrows in space or functions."}, {"duration": 3.69, "start": 841.86, "text": "For example, this is why just about every textbook you'll find will"}, {"duration": 3.635, "start": 845.55, "text": "define linear transformations in terms of additivity and scaling,"}, {"duration": 4.075, "start": 849.185, "text": "rather than talking about gridlines remaining parallel and evenly spaced."}, {"duration": 3.641, "start": 853.26, "text": "Even though the latter is more intuitive, and at least in my view,"}, {"duration": 4.359, "start": 856.901, "text": "more helpful for first-time learners, even if it is specific to one situation."}, {"duration": 4.3, "start": 862.62, "text": "So the mathematician's answer to what are vectors is to just ignore the question."}, {"duration": 3.76, "start": 867.5, "text": "In the modern theory, the form that vectors take doesn't really matter."}, {"duration": 4.425, "start": 871.86, "text": "Arrows, lists of numbers, functions, pi creatures, really, it can be anything,"}, {"duration": 4.935, "start": 876.285, "text": "so long as there's some notion of adding and scaling vectors that follows these rules."}, {"duration": 3.02, "start": 881.86, "text": "It's like asking what the number 3 really is."}, {"duration": 4.381, "start": 885.38, "text": "Whenever it comes up concretely, it's in the context of some triplet of things,"}, {"duration": 4.492, "start": 889.761, "text": "but in math, it's treated as an abstraction for all possible triplets of things,"}, {"duration": 3.827, "start": 894.253, "text": "and lets you reason about all possible triplets using a single idea."}, {"duration": 3.104, "start": 899.12, "text": "Same goes with vectors, which have many embodiments,"}, {"duration": 4.776, "start": 902.224, "text": "but math abstracts them all into a single, intangible notion of a vector space."}, {"duration": 3.439, "start": 908.86, "text": "But, as anyone watching this series knows, I think it's better"}, {"duration": 3.883, "start": 912.299, "text": "to begin reasoning about vectors in a concrete, visualizable setting,"}, {"duration": 2.718, "start": 916.182, "text": "like 2D space, with arrows rooted at the origin."}, {"duration": 4.721, "start": 919.66, "text": "But as you learn more linear algebra, know that these tools apply much more generally,"}, {"duration": 4.721, "start": 924.381, "text": "and that this is the underlying reason why textbooks and lectures tend to be phrased,"}, {"duration": 0.988, "start": 929.102, "text": "well, abstractly."}, {"duration": 4.2, "start": 931.94, "text": "So with that, folks, I think I'll call it an in to this essence of linear algebra series."}, {"duration": 3.856, "start": 936.14, "text": "If you've watched and understood the videos, I really do believe that you"}, {"duration": 3.804, "start": 939.996, "text": "have a solid foundation in the underlying intuitions of linear algebra."}, {"duration": 2.813, "start": 944.64, "text": "This is not the same thing as learning the full topic, of course,"}, {"duration": 3.202, "start": 947.453, "text": "that's something that can only really come from working through problems,"}, {"duration": 3.851, "start": 950.655, "text": "but the learning you do moving forward could be substantially more efficient if you have"}, {"duration": 1.514, "start": 954.506, "text": "all the right intuitions in place."}, {"duration": 3.34, "start": 956.66, "text": "So, have fun applying those intuitions, and best of luck with your future learning."}], "video_id": "TgKwz5Ikpc8"}